{"type":"message","id":"7b9f8a23","parentId":"35810700","timestamp":"2026-04-30T21:34:10.752Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait — I think I'm confused about the timeline.\n\nBobby said:\n- Mom gave him $13,000\n- He paid off all Affirm payments (~ $1,400)\n- He has $2,000 in savings and $9,710.30 in checking = $11,710.30\n\nBut now he's saying he used the $13,000 to pay the Affirm payments.\n\nLet me re-read...\n\nEarlier he said: \"my mom gave me 13000. i paid off all the affirm payments and now i have 2,000 in my savings and 9710.30 in my checking\"\n\nSo the sequence was:\n1. Mom gave $13,000\n2. He paid off Affirm payments (~$1,400)\n3. Left with $11,600... but he said he has $11,710.30 total\n\nActually the numbers don't add up perfectly. $13,000 - $1,400 = $11,600. But he says he has $2,000 savings + $9,710.30 checking = $11,710.30. That's $110 more than expected.\n\nMaybe he had some of his own money mixed in. Or maybe I'm misreading something.\n\nBut the key question is: did he USE the $13,000 (which is now gone) to pay Affirm? Or does he still have the $13,000?\n\nHe just said \"i used the 13000 to pay the affirm payments. does that change anything?\"\n\nOH. So the $13,000 IS GONE. It's not sitting in his account anymore. The $11,710.30 is HIS money that he had before/besides the $13,000.\n\nSo the $13,000 went to Affirm. He has $11,710.30 of his own money.\n \nIf the $13,000 is already gone and he only has $11,710.30 now, then paying off the 4 cards would cost $5,997.44 — leaving him with $5,712.86. But he owes his mom $13,000 total, which is separate from what he just spent on Affirm. I need to clarify whether the $13,000 he owes her is what's left after the Affirm payments or if that's a separate obligation entirely.","thinkingSignature":"e7ceb4c782e5f0bf3022f70e61e1f5e89f46200d00f6805d63c738d808be7f90"},{"type":"text","text":"Wait — I need to clarify.\n\nSo the $13,000 from your mom went to the Affirm payments